# Proposed Update — apply-revisions.md

**Source:** SkillTest R1.C case-results, case-overclaim evaluations of
nature-polishing.
**Status:** Draft only. Do not apply to
`/Users/mjm/MinionsOS/minions/roles/writer/skills/apply-revisions.md` until
the user explicitly approves the R1 synthesis port plan.

## What to add

The current `apply-revisions.md` covers reviewer-requested-change
incorporation. Add two cross-cutting rules at the start of the Procedure
section.

### Add Rule: Paper-type diagnosis as first move

Add as the first numbered step of the Procedure section:

> **Diagnose paper type before any sentence-level edit.** Identify whether
> this is a research / methods / hypothesis-based / algorithmic / device
> paper. Different paper types require different narrative logic:
> - Research paper: phenomenon → mechanism → significance
> - Methods paper: existing methods' limits → new method → fair comparison
> - Hypothesis-based: testable claim → support → boundary
> - Algorithmic / device: procedure → reliability + advantage demonstration
>
> Do NOT use one narrative logic across paper types. A Discussion-tense
> sentence in a methods-paper Results section is the most common
> register-mixing failure.

Evidence: SkillTest R1.C case-results. Candidate emitted an explicit
"Diagnosed paper type / failure mode" footer ("Research paper, Results
paragraph; main failure mode was Results / Discussion mixing") that bound
its sentence-level decisions to a register. Baseline did the right thing
by reflex but didn't articulate the diagnosis; in edge cases (mixed-type
manuscripts, methods-paper Results sections) the reflex breaks down.

### Add Rule: Results vs Discussion verb taxonomy

Add as a hard rule under sentence-level discipline:

> **Results sentences use observation verbs:** was detected, increased,
> decreased, showed, enabled, achieved, abolished, replicated.
>
> **Discussion sentences use interpretive verbs:** may reflect, suggests,
> could indicate, is likely due to, may facilitate, would support, is
> consistent with.
>
> A Results paragraph drifting into Discussion syntax (and vice versa)
> is a register failure that no amount of polish can fix at the sentence
> level — the paragraph needs to be re-anchored to the right section
> first.

Evidence: SkillTest R1.C case-results. Source paragraph mixed
`we believe / may reflect / likely due to / strongly indicates` (all
Discussion verbs) with `was observed / 3.2-fold / p=0.011` (Results
content). Both baseline and candidate cleaned this up; candidate's
extra discipline came from naming the verb family it was downgrading
to ("linking the co-activator to the measured expression change" — pure
observation, no claim about necessity).

## What to NOT add

The "diagnosis footer" emitted in candidate's revision notes is useful
during reviewer-coach mode but should NOT appear in production manuscript
prose. The skill should distinguish:
- Production output: polished prose only.
- Revision-coach output: polished prose + revision notes + diagnosis footer.

## Why these are the right additions

R1.C had:
- case-results +2 (Calibrates) — paper-type diagnosis + verb taxonomy
- case-overclaim +4 (Calibrates) — boundary specificity (covered in
  `aspect-note.md.diff`, separate update)

The verb taxonomy is the highest-leverage cross-section rule from R1.C;
the paper-type diagnosis is the highest-leverage process rule. Both
belong in `apply-revisions.md` because that's the skill that fires when a
reviewer has asked for revisions and the writer is about to start editing.
